# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: uuid-generation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:uuid-generation/crypto-randomuuid] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:uuid-generation/crypto-randomuuid] It’s been available across browsers since March 2022.
[src:uuid-generation/crypto-randomuuid] The **`randomUUID()`** method of the `Crypto` interface is used to generate a v4 UUID using a cryptographically secure random number generator.
[src:uuid-generation/crypto-randomuuid] A string containing a randomly generated, 36 character long v4 UUID.
[src:uuid-generation/getrandomvalues] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:uuid-generation/getrandomvalues] The **`Crypto.getRandomValues()`** method lets you get cryptographically strong random values.
[src:uuid-generation/getrandomvalues] The array given as the parameter is filled with random numbers (random in its cryptographic meaning).
[src:uuid-generation/getrandomvalues] To guarantee enough performance, implementations are not using a truly random number generator, but they are using a pseudo-random number generator *seeded* with a value with enough entropy.
[src:uuid-generation/getrandomvalues] The pseudo-random number generator algorithm (PRNG) may vary across user agents, but is suitable for cryptographic purposes.
[src:uuid-generation/getrandomvalues] `getRandomValues()` is the only member of the `Crypto` interface which can be used from an insecure context.
[src:uuid-generation/getrandomvalues] An integer-based `TypedArray`, that is one of: `Int8Array`, `Uint8Array`, `Uint8ClampedArray`, `Int16Array`, `Uint16Array`, `Int32Array`, `Uint32Array`, `BigInt64Array`, `BigUint64Array` (but **not** `Float16Array`, `Float32Array` nor `Float64Array`).
[src:uuid-generation/getrandomvalues] All elements in the array will be overwritten with random numbers.
[src:uuid-generation/getrandomvalues] The same array passed as `typedArray` but with its contents replaced with the newly generated random numbers.
[src:uuid-generation/getrandomvalues] Note that `typedArray` is modified in-place, and no copy is made.
[src:uuid-generation/getrandomvalues] Thrown if the `byteLength` of `typedArray` exceeds 65,536.
[src:uuid-generation/getrandomvalues] Prefer the `generateKey()` method for key generation, which is guaranteed to be running in a secure context.
[src:uuid-generation/getrandomvalues] There is no minimum degree of entropy mandated by the Web Cryptography specification.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Various applications of randomness have led to the development of different methods for generating random data.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Some of these have existed since ancient times, including well-known examples like the rolling of dice, coin flipping, the shuffling of playing cards, the use of yarrow stalks (for divination) in the I Ching, as well as countless other techniques.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Because of the mechanical nature of these techniques, generating large quantities of sufficiently random numbers (important in statistics) required much work and time.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Thus, results would sometimes be collected and distributed as random number tables.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Several computational methods for pseudorandom number generation exist.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] All fall short of the goal of true randomness, although they may meet, with varying success, some of the statistical tests for randomness intended to measure how unpredictable their results are (that is, to what degree their patterns are discernible).
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] This generally makes them unusable for applications such as cryptography.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] However, carefully designed *cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generators* (CSPRNGS) also exist, with special features specifically designed for use in cryptography.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Random number generators have applications in gambling, statistical sampling, computer simulation, cryptography, completely randomized design, and other areas where producing an unpredictable result is desirable.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Generally, in applications having unpredictability as the paramount feature, such as in security applications, hardware generators are generally preferred over pseudorandom algorithms, where feasible.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Pseudorandom number generators are very useful in developing Monte Carlo-method simulations, as debugging is facilitated by the ability to run the same sequence of random numbers again by starting from the same *random seed*.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] They are also used in cryptography – so long as the *seed* is secret.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] The sender and receiver can generate the same set of numbers automatically to use as keys.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] The generation of pseudorandom numbers is an important and common task in computer programming.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] While cryptography and certain numerical algorithms require a very high degree of *apparent* randomness, many other operations only need a modest amount of unpredictability.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Some simple examples might be presenting a user with a "random quote of the day", or determining which way a computer-controlled adversary might move in a computer game.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Weaker forms of *randomness* are used in hash algorithms and in creating amortized searching and sorting algorithms.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Some applications that appear at first sight to be suitable for randomization are in fact not quite so simple.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] For instance, a system that "randomly" selects music tracks for a background music system must only *appear* random, and may even have ways to control the selection of music: a truly random system would have no restriction on the same item appearing two or three times in succession.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] There are two principal methods used to generate random numbers.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] The first method measures some physical phenomenon that is expected to be random and then compensates for possible biases in the measurement process.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Example sources include measuring atmospheric noise, thermal noise, and other external electromagnetic and quantum phenomena.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] For example, cosmic background radiation or radioactive decay as measured over short timescales represent sources of natural entropy (as a measure of unpredictability or surprise of the number generation process).
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] The speed at which entropy can be obtained from natural sources is dependent on the underlying physical phenomena being measured.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Thus, sources of naturally occurring *true* entropy are said to be blocking – they are rate-limited until enough entropy is harvested to meet the demand.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] On some Unix-like systems, including most Linux distributions, the pseudo device file /dev/random will block until sufficient entropy is harvested from the environment.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Due to this blocking behavior, large bulk reads from /dev/random, such as filling a hard disk drive with random bits, can often be slow on systems that use this type of entropy source.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] The second method uses computational algorithms that can produce long sequences of apparently random results, which are in fact completely determined by a shorter initial value, known as a seed value or key.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] As a result, the entire seemingly random sequence can be reproduced if the seed value is known.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] This type of random number generator is often called a pseudorandom number generator.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] This type of generator typically does not rely on sources of naturally occurring entropy, though it may be periodically seeded by natural sources.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] This generator type is non-blocking, so they are not rate-limited by an external event, making large bulk reads a possibility.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Standard cryptographic designs take a hybrid approach, using randomness harvested from natural sources to seed a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generators (CSPRNGs).
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Hardware random number generators generally produce only a limited number of random bits per second.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] In order to increase the available output data rate, they are often used to generate the "seed" for a faster PRNG.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] PRNG also helps with the noise source "anonymization" (whitening out the noise source identifying characteristics) and entropy extraction.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] With a proper PRNG algorithm selected (cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator, CSPRNG), the combination can satisfy the requirements of Federal Information Processing Standards and Common Criteria standards.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] The earliest methods for generating random numbers, such as dice, coin flipping and roulette wheels, are still used today, mainly in games and gambling, as they tend to be too slow for most applications in statistics and cryptography.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Many natural phenomena generate low-level, statistically random "noise" signals, including thermal and shot noise, jitter and metastability of electronic circuits, Brownian motion, and atmospheric noise.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Researchers also used the photoelectric effect, involving a beam splitter, other quantum phenomena, and even nuclear decay (due to practical considerations the latter, as well as the atmospheric noise, is not viable except for fairly restricted applications or online distribution services).
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] While "classical" (non-quantum) phenomena are not truly random, an unpredictable physical system is usually acceptable as a source of randomness, so the qualifiers "true" and "physical" are used interchangeably.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] A hardware random number generator is expected to output near-perfect random numbers ("full entropy").
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] For performance and security reasons, most random number generators use PRNGs in their construction (this architecture is actually mandated in the industrial standards like NIST SP 800-90A).
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] A pseudorandom number generator (PRNG), also known as a deterministic random bit generator (DRBG), is an algorithm for generating a sequence of numbers whose properties approximate the properties of sequences of random numbers.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] The PRNG-generated sequence is not truly random, because it is completely determined by an initial value, called the PRNG's *seed* (which may include truly random values).
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Although sequences that are closer to truly random can be generated using hardware random number generators, *pseudorandom number generators* are important in practice for their speed in number generation and their reproducibility.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] PRNGs are central in applications such as simulations (e.g. for the Monte Carlo method), electronic games (e.g. for procedural generation), and cryptography.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Cryptographic applications require the output not to be predictable from earlier outputs, and more elaborate algorithms, which do not inherit the linearity of simpler PRNGs, are needed.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Good statistical properties are a central requirement for the output of a PRNG.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] In general, careful mathematical analysis is required to have any confidence that a PRNG generates numbers that are sufficiently close to random to suit the intended use.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Random number generation may also be performed by humans, in the form of collecting various inputs from end users and using them as a randomization source.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] However, most studies find that human subjects have some degree of non-randomness when attempting to produce a random sequence of e.g., digits or letters.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] They may alternate too much between choices when compared to a good random generator; thus, this approach is not widely used.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] However, for the very reason that humans perform poorly in this task, human random number generation can be used as a tool to gain insights into brain functions otherwise not accessible.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Even given a source of plausible random numbers (perhaps from a quantum mechanically based hardware generator), obtaining numbers which are completely unbiased takes care.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] In addition, behavior of these generators often changes with temperature, power supply voltage, the age of the device, or other outside interference.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Generated random numbers are sometimes subjected to statistical tests before use to ensure that the underlying source is still working, and then post-processed to improve their statistical properties.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] An example would be the TRNG9803 hardware random number generator, which uses an entropy measurement as a hardware test, and then post-processes the random sequence with a shift register stream cipher.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] It is generally hard to use statistical tests to validate the generated random numbers.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Wang and Nicol proposed a distance-based statistical testing technique that is used to identify the weaknesses of several random generators.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Li and Wang proposed a method of testing random numbers based on laser chaotic entropy sources using Brownian motion properties.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Statistical tests are also used to give confidence that the post-processed final output from a random number generator is truly unbiased, with numerous randomness test suites being developed.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Most random number generators natively work with integers or individual bits, so an extra step is required to arrive at the *canonical* uniform distribution between 0 and 1.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] The implementation is not as trivial as dividing the integer by its maximum possible value.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] The nature of floating-point math itself means there exists more precision the closer the number is to zero.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] This extra precision is usually not used due to the sheer number of bits required.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Rounding error in division may bias the result.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] At worst, a supposedly excluded bound may be drawn contrary to expectations based on real-number math.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] The mainstream algorithm, used by OpenJDK, Rust, and NumPy, is described in a proposal for C++'s STL.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] It does not use the extra precision and suffers from bias only in the last bit due to rounding half to even.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Other numeric concerns are warranted when shifting this *canonical* uniform distribution to a different range.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] A proposed method for the Swift programming language claims to use the full precision everywhere.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Uniformly distributed integers are commonly used in algorithms such as the Fisher–Yates shuffle.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Again, a naive implementation may induce a modulo bias into the result, so more involved algorithms must be used.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] A method that nearly never performs division was described in 2018 by Daniel Lemire, with the current state-of-the-art being the arithmetic encoding-inspired 2021 "optimal algorithm" by Stephen Canon of Apple Inc.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Most 0 to 1 RNGs include 0 but exclude 1, while others include or exclude both.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Given a source of uniform random numbers, there are a couple of methods to create a new random source that corresponds to a probability density function.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] One method called the inversion method, involves integrating up to an area greater than or equal to the random number (which should be generated between 0 and 1 for proper distributions).
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] A second method called the acceptance-rejection method, involves choosing an x and y value and testing whether the function of x is greater than the y value.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Otherwise, the x value is rejected and the algorithm tries again.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] As an example for rejection sampling, to generate a pair of statistically independent standard normally distributed random numbers (*x*, *y*), one may first generate the polar coordinates (*r*, *θ*), where *r*2~χ22 and *θ*~UNIFORM(0,2π) (see Box–Muller transform).
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] The outputs of multiple independent RNGs can be combined (for example, using a bit-wise XOR operation) to provide a combined RNG at least as good as the best RNG used.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] This is referred to as software whitening.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Computational and hardware random number generators are sometimes combined to reflect the benefits of both kinds.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Computational random number generators can typically generate pseudorandom numbers much faster than physical generators, while physical generators can generate true randomness.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Some computations making use of a random number generator can be summarized as the computation of a total or average value, such as the computation of integrals by the Monte Carlo method.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] For such problems, it may be possible to find a more accurate solution by the use of so-called low-discrepancy sequences, also called quasirandom numbers.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Such sequences have a definite pattern that fills in gaps evenly, qualitatively speaking; a truly random sequence may, and usually does, leave larger gaps.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Since much cryptography depends on a cryptographically secure random number generator for key and cryptographic nonce generation, if a random number generator can be made predictable, it can be used as backdoor by an attacker to break the encryption.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] The NSA is reported to have inserted a backdoor into the NIST certified cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator Dual EC DRBG.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] If for example an SSL connection is created using this random number generator, then according to Matthew Green it would allow NSA to determine the state of the random number generator, and thereby eventually be able to read all data sent over the SSL connection.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] Even though it was apparent that Dual_EC_DRBG was a very poor and possibly backdoored pseudorandom number generator long before the NSA backdoor was confirmed in 2013, it had seen significant usage in practice until 2013, for example by the prominent security company RSA Security.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] There have subsequently been accusations that RSA Security knowingly inserted a NSA backdoor into its products, possibly as part of the Bullrun program.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] RSA has denied knowingly inserting a backdoor into its products.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] It has also been theorized that hardware RNGs could be secretly modified to have less entropy than stated, which would make encryption using the hardware RNG susceptible to attack.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] One such method that has been published works by modifying the dopant mask of the chip, which would be undetectable to optical reverse-engineering.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] For example, for random number generation in Linux, it is seen as unacceptable to use Intel's RDRAND hardware RNG without mixing in the RDRAND output with other sources of entropy to counteract any backdoors in the hardware RNG, especially after the revelation of the NSA Bullrun program.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] In 2010, a U.S. lottery draw was rigged by the information security director of the Multi-State Lottery Association (MUSL), who surreptitiously installed backdoor malware on the MUSL's secure RNG computer during routine maintenance.
[src:uuid-generation/random-number-generation] During the hacks the man won a total amount of $16,500,000 over multiple years.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] A **universally unique identifier** (**UUID**) is a 128-bit number used to identify information in computer systems.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The term **globally unique identifier** (**GUID**) is also used, typically in software created by Microsoft.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] When generated according to the standards, UUIDs are, for practical purposes, unique.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Their uniqueness does not depend on a central registration authority or coordination between the parties generating them, unlike most other numbering schemes.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] While the probability that a UUID will be duplicated is not zero, it is close enough to zero to be negligible.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, anyone can create large numbers of UUIDs and use them as identifiers with near certainty that they do not duplicate UUIDs that have been, or will be, created by others, with the only coordination required to achieve uniqueness being conformance with the UUID standards.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Information labeled with UUIDs by independent parties can therefore coexist in the same databases or channels, with a negligible probability of duplication.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Adoption of UUIDs is widespread, with many computing platforms providing support for generating them and for parsing their textual representation.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Apollo Computer used UUIDs in the Network Computing System (NCS), launched in 1987, with a design inspired by the 64-bit unique identifiers of Domain/OS, an earlier Apollo operating system.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Microsoft Windows platforms adopted the NCS (and later, the DCE) design as "Globally Unique Identifiers" (GUIDs) in the early nineties.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Somewhat later, the Open Software Foundation (OSF) used UUIDs in its Distributed Computing Environment (DCE), with a design partly based on the NCS UUIDs.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] This was documented in the DCE 1.1 RPC specification in 1996, and in the DCE 1.1 Authentication and Security Services specification, published in 1997.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] ISO/IEC documented the DCE design in 1996, in ISO/IEC 11578:1996 "Information technology – Open Systems Interconnection – Remote Procedure Call".
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] In July 2005, the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) published the Standards-Track RFC 4122., which also registered a URN namespace for UUIDs.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The ITU had meanwhile also standardized UUIDs, based on the previous standards and early versions of RFC 4122, in ITU-T Rec.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] This was technically equivalent to RFC 4122.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The current IETF specification is RFC 9562, a Proposed Standard published in May 2024.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] This defined three new UUID versions (6–8) of the DCE variant.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The UUIDs currently in use are the DCE/IETF design, with provision for backwards compatibility with "legacy" Apollo NCS UUIDs and Microsoft GUIDs.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The authors of RFC 4122 were Paul Leach, Michael Mealling, and Rich Salz, and the authors of the initial 1997 Internet Draft were Leach and Salz.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Leach had been the Architect of Domain/OS, had continued at Apollo as a designer of NCS, and then, as a Microsoft Distinguished Architect, contributed to the design of OLE/COM/DCOM, carrying the concept of UUIDs to that project.Leach was also one of the authors of RFC 9562.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Salz was a member of the DCE team at the Open Software Foundation.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Apollo had merged in 1989 with Hewlett-Packard, a founding member of the OSF.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Former NCS team-members, having become HP employees, brought UUIDs to OSF DCE.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Mealling was a prominent IETF member, holding a seat on the Internet Engineering Steering Group, and was heavily involved in IETF work on URNs.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 4122 brought all these strands together.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The meaning of the bits is determined by the *variant*, of which three are defined.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Of these, the most common is variant 1, with the other variants being for backwards compatibility with previous formats or for future definition.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Variants 1 and 2 have "versions", which further define the interpretation of the UUID.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The *variant* field is in a variable number of the most-significant bits of the ninth byte.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The OSF DCE and Microsoft COM/DCOM variants (1 & 2, respectively) have *versions*, indicated by the value of the high four bits of the seventh byte of the UUID.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] In textual representations of the UUID, this is the hex digit after the second hyphen.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Variant 0 Apollo NCS UUIDs do not have versions, being sub-typed via "address families" rather than versions.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 9562, which defined versions 6, 7, and 8 stated that variants other than the OSF DCE variant 1 were "out of scope" of the RFC, leaving it to Microsoft to define new versions for variant 2.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] However, versions 1 through 5, standardized in RFC 4122, are the same in the Microsoft variant, except for byte-ordering.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Version 1 concatenates the 48-bit MAC address of the "node" (that is, the computer generating the UUID), with a 60-bit timestamp.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] On systems with 64-bit EUI-64 "MAC addresses", the least significant 48 bits are used.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] A 48-bit random number may also be used.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The timestamp is the number of 100-nanosecond intervals since midnight 15 October 1582 Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), the date on which the Gregorian calendar was first adopted.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 4122 states that the time value rolls over in A.D.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] 3409,depending on the algorithm used, which implies that the 60-bit timestamp is a signed quantity.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] However some software, such as the libuuid library, treats the timestamp as unsigned, putting the rollover time in A.D.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] A 13-bit or 14-bit "uniquifying" clock sequence extends the timestamp in order to handle cases where the processor clock does not advance fast enough, or where there are multiple processors and UUID generators per node.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] When UUIDs are generated faster than the system clock can advance, the lower bits of the timestamp and the clock sequence can be incremented to simulate greater precision and ensure uniqueness.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] With each version-1 UUID corresponding to a single point in space (the node) and time (intervals and clock sequence), the chance of two properly generated version-1 UUIDs being unintentionally the same is practically nil.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Since the time and clock sequence total 74 bits, 274 (1.8×1022, or 18 sextillion) version-1 UUIDs can be generated per node ID, at a maximal average rate of 163 billion per second per node ID.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Version 6 is the same as version 1 except for the order of the timestamp bits.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] In version 6, timestamp bits are ordered from most significant to least significant.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] This allows systems to sort version-6 UUIDs in order of creation simply by sorting them lexically.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] By reinstating the original NCS hi-lo byte order of the timestamp to enable sortability, version 6 is even more similar to "legacy" variant 0 NCS UUIDs than version 1.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] RFCs 4122 and 9562 reserve version 2 for "DCE security" UUIDs; but do not provide any details.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Many UUID implementations and libraries omit version 2.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] However, the specification of version-2 UUIDs is provided by the DCE 1.1 Authentication and Security Services specification.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Version-2 UUIDs are similar to version 1, except that the least significant 8 bits of the clock sequence are replaced by a "local domain" number, and the least significant 32 bits of the 60-bit Gregorian timestamp are replaced by an integer identifier meaningful within the specified local domain.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] On POSIX systems, local-domain numbers 0 and 1 are for user ids (UIDs) and group ids (GIDs) respectively, and other local-domain numbers are site-defined.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] On non-POSIX systems, all local domain numbers are site-defined.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, version-2 UUIDs are a way to combine a 32-bit local, node-scoped identifier of a specified 8-bit type ("domain") with the identifier of the node and a Gregorian-origin timestamp, transforming the node-scoped identifier into one that is universally unique.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The tradeoff is that the timestamp is low-res in comparison to the timestamps in version 1, ticking only once once every 429.49 seconds, a little more than 7 minutes, quite different from the 100 nanosecond ticks in version 1.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Version-3 and version-5 UUIDs are generated by hashing a namespace identifier and name.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Version 3 uses MD5 as the hashing algorithm, and version 5 uses SHA-1.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] This is useful when systems need deterministically to generate the same UUID based on a set of other names or identifiers, without coordination.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The namespace identifier is itself a UUID.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The RFC provides constant UUIDs to represent the namespaces for URLs, fully qualified domain names, object identifiers, and X.500 distinguished names; but any desired UUID may be used as a namespace designator.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] There is an IANA registry for additional namespace ids.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] To determine the version-3 UUID corresponding to a given namespace and name, the UUID of the namespace is transformed to a string of bytes, concatenated with the input name, then hashed with MD5, yielding 128 bits.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Then six or seven bits are replaced by fixed values, the four-bit version (e.g.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] 00112 for version 3), and the two- or three-bit UUID "variant" (e.g.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] 102 indicating an RFC 9562 UUIDs, or 1102 indicating a legacy Microsoft GUID).
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Since 6 or 7 bits are thus predetermined, only 121 or 122 bits contribute to the uniqueness of the UUID.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Version-5 UUIDs are similar, but SHA-1 is used instead of MD5.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Since SHA-1 generates 160-bit digests, the digest is truncated to 128 bits before the version and variant bits are replaced.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Version-3 and version-5 UUIDs have the property that, given the version, the same namespace and name will map to the same UUID.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] However, neither the namespace nor name can be determined from the UUID, even if one of them is specified, except by brute-force search.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 4122 recommends version 5 (SHA-1) over version 3 (MD5).
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] This is because it is believed that MD5 is more prone to collisions than SHA-1, though MD5 is somewhat faster.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The RFC warns against use of UUIDs of any version as security capabilities.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] As in other UUIDs, four bits are used to indicate version 4, and two or three bits to indicate the variant (102 or 1102 for variants 1 and 2 respectively).
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, for variant 1 (that is, most UUIDs) a random version-4 UUID will have six predetermined variant and version bits, leaving 122 bits for the randomly generated part, for a total of 2122, or 5.3×1036 (5.3 undecillion) possible version-4, variant-1 UUIDs.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] There are half as many possible version-4, variant 2 UUIDs (legacy GUIDs) because there is one less random bit available, three bits being consumed for the variant.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Version-7 UUIDs are intended as monotonically ascending, creation-time-ordered, lexically sortable keys in large databases and distributed systems, contributing to locality and performance.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] With version 7 as database keys, "new" records are inserted at the logical end of the key sequence, and records which are close in time are near each other in the key sequence.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] This contrasts with the random version 4, which when used as database keys, are evenly and randomly dispersed across the key sequence, even when the underlying records are close in time, negatively affecting performance in many types of databases.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The 48-bit timestamps may be altered, fuzzed, or smeared for the sake of monotonicity and privacy, and it is explicitly stated that there is no requirement about how close a timestamp needs to be to the actual (Unix) time.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] But the intent is clear that the timestamps should be monontonic and approximate Unix time, and the RFC states that custom UUID version 8 should be used for timestamp-based designs that are not Unix time.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Unlike some other UUID versions, version-7 UUIDs do not incorporate MAC addresses, and can steer clear of the privacy issues associated with them.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] In a custom UUID, the version is `8`, and the variant bits must be `10`, totaling 6 bits.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The remaining 122 bits are not specified.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] According to the RFC, version-8 UUIDs are intended for experimental and vendor-specific use cases.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The RFC suggests, for example, that this version might be used for a name/hash-based identifier generated with a newer hashing function than those specified for UUID versions 3 (MD5) and 5 (SHA-1).
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The RFC also suggests that version 8 can be used for timestamp-based UUID designs that do not fit within versions 6 or 7, such as a different epoch.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] But version 8 is not restricted to such scenarios.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] In essence, version-8 UUIDs are 122 opaque bits, combined with six version and variant bits, allowing them to be separated from other UUID forms.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Unlike other versions, the RFC does not mandate a specific bit layout or generation algorithm, and they are not to be assumed to be unique.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] In addition, as with other UUID versions, there is no concept of version subtypes.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The uniqueness of the UUIDs based on network-card MAC addresses also depends on network-card manufacturers properly assigning unique MAC addresses to their cards which, like other manufacturing processes, is subject to error.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] MAC addresses also may come from sources other than network cards.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] For example, virtual machines receive a MAC address from a range that is configurable in the hypervisor, and some operating systems permit the end user to customise the MAC address, notably OpenWrt.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] When a device has an EUI-64 64-bit "MAC address", using the least significant 48 bits of it, as recommended by the RFC, may result in the node ID part of the UUID being duplicated.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, node IDs based on MAC addresses may not be globally unique.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Usage of the node's network card MAC address for the node ID does often mean that version-1, -2, and -6 UUIDs can be tracked back to the computer that created them.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Such UUIDs can be used to infer what kind of hardware is being used to generate the UUIDs.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Documents can sometimes be traced to the computers where they were created or edited through UUIDs embedded into them by word processing software.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] This privacy hole was used when locating the creator of the Melissa virus.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 9562 does allow the MAC address in a version-1, -2 or -6 UUID to be replaced by a random 48-bit node ID, either because the node does not have a MAC address, or because it is not desirable to include it.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] In that case, the RFC requires that the least significant bit of the first octet of the node ID should be set to 1.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] This corresponds to the multicast bit in MAC addresses, and setting it serves to differentiate UUIDs where the node ID is randomly generated from UUIDs based on MAC addresses from network cards, which typically have unicast MAC addresses.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Versions 1, 2, 6, and 7 are based on, and expose, the time when the UUID was generated, which often corresponds to the creation of a record, or an historical event.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] If associated with people or their activity, it may be possible to infer a person's age or the precise time of their activities from UUIDs.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] It may be possible to determine from time-based monotonically-ascending UUIDs when a system went live, or what objects in a system are new or recently updated.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] If the identified objects represent product orders or user sign-ups, for example, it may be possible to determine user growth or sales volume over time from the UUIDs.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, time-based UUIDs, if publicly visible, may leak personal or business information, raise privacy concerns, and facilitate unwanted data mining.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Concerning the time-ordering and sortability of UUIDs, version 1 and 2 start "in the middle" with the 32 low bits of the timestamp.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] These two versions, along with 3–5 and 8, do not sort lexically into time order.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The role of the timestamp in these UUID versions was not to make UUIDs readily orderable in time but rather to achieve universal uniqueness by fixing the generation in space and time.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Versions 6 and 7 prioritize the timestamp's role in database indexing, allowing for lexical sorting of records into chronological order.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] However, RFC 9562 provides significant implementation flexibility for version 7, defining a general framework rather than a rigid bit-layout for optional sub-millisecond timestamp precision, counters, and randomness.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The specification allows the 48-bit Unix timestamp to be adjusted or "fuzzed" to maintain monotonicity (ensuring IDs created in rapid succession always increase) or to enhance privacy.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Because the RFC does not define a strict maximum deviation from actual Unix time, different implementations may vary in how they balance chronological accuracy against these other requirements.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Consequently, the lexical sortability of versions 6 and 7 UUIDs is most consistent when generated by the same library or system.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Mixing UUIDs from different sources, or interleaving different versions and variants in a single database, can degrade the time-ordering and index locality that these versions were designed to provide.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 9562 does not mandate a minimum number of random bits for version 7; it allows the sub-millisecond precision and monotonicity counter fields to occupy the remainder of the 128-bit structure.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Consequently, collision resistance and guessability depend entirely on the specific implementation's allocation of these bits.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] This is a "variant 0" NCS UUID with an address family of "0", defined in NCS as "unspecified or uninitialized".
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The Max UUID, sometimes also called the Omni UUID, is `FFFFFFFF-FFFF-FFFF-FFFF-FFFFFFFFFFFF` (that is, all set bits).
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] This is intended to be used for expressing "end of UUID list".
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 4122 incorporated legacy NCS UUIDs as "variant 0" of the new format by overlapping the variant bits of the new format with the NCS Address Family field.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Since the highest address family value defined in NCS is 13 (hex 00 to 0D), the most significant bit in the variant octet is always 0 for extant NCS UUIDs, while this bit is 1 in the newer three IETF variants.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] In effect, NCS address families 0–127 became the new "variant 0", while the numbering space of NCS address families 128–255, which was undefined in NCS, was rededicated to variant-1-to-3 IETF and Microsoft UUIDs.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The result was that legacy NCS UUIDs and variant-1-to-3 UUIDs were separated and could coexist in the same databases, and on the same communication channels.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The legacy Apollo NCS UUID has the format described in the previous table.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The OSF DCE UUID variant is described in RFC 9562.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The Microsoft COM / DCOM UUID has its variant described in the Microsoft documentation, but for versions 1 to 5, is generally the same as the DCE variant, except for the extra variant bit and byte-ordering.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] (See next section.) Variant 2 does not have versions 6 to 8.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The interpretation of the various bit-blocks varies in variants 1 and 2 according to the "version".
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] In variant 2, data_a, data_b, version|data_c are byte-swapped and variant|data_d and data_e are not byte-swapped.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Variant 1 UUIDs are sequentially encoded in big-endian.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] In contrast, variant 2 UUIDs ("GUIDs"): historically used in Microsoft COM/OLE libraries, have a mixed-endian format, with the first three fields (corresponding to version-1 timestamp subfields) being little-endian, while the final two fields are emitted as big-endian arrays of bytes.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The example UUID above, if it were a variant 2 UUID, would be encoded on the wire as `33 22 11 00 55 44 77 66 88 99 aa bb cc dd ee ff`.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] All versions under variant 2 are emitted with this byte ordering, including versions not containing numeric fields, such as 3,4, and 5.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] In most cases, UUIDs are represented as hexadecimal values separated by hyphens.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Most used is the 8-4-4-4-12 format, a string of 32 hexadecimal digits with four hyphens, `xxxxxxxx-xxxx-vxxx-wxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx`.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The hyphens separate the version-1 fields but the same format is commonly used for all versions.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Every hexadecimal digit represents 4 bits; `v` represents the version nibble; and the high-order one to three bits of `w` are the variant.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The Windows registry format is the same but wraps the UUID in `{}` braces.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The byte-ordering differences of variant 2 are applicable in binary storage or transmission on the wire, and do not affect the textual presentation of the UUID.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Though they are still occasionally omitted, the format with hyphens was introduced with the newer variant system.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The first part is the time (time_high and time_low combined).
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The family field comes directly after the first dot, so in this case `0d` (13 in decimal) for DDS (Data Distribution Service).
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The remaining parts, each separated with a dot, are the node bytes.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Lowercase hexadecimal digits are preferred.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] X.667 requires lowercase on generation, but also requires the uppercase version to be accepted on input.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Since UUIDs are 128-bit numbers, other formats are possible, and occasionally seen, such as decimal digits or binary.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 4122 registers the "uuid" namespace for URNs.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The normal 8-4-4-4-12 format is used for this.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] It is also possible to make an OID out of a UUID, which in turn provides another way to make a URN from it.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The unsigned decimal form of the UUID is prefixed with `2.25`, which represents the `{joint-iso-itu-t(2) uuid(25)}` "arc" within the OID namespace.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] This may be further prefixed with `urn:oid:` to make a second form of URN for UUIDs.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] In general, the `uuid` URN is recommended over the `oid` URN.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] A collision occurs when the same UUID is generated more than once and is assigned to different referents.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] In the case of many standard version-1, -2, or -6 UUIDs using unique MAC addresses and/or timestamps, collisions can occur only as a result of error, such as manufacturing problems, skewed clocks, or software bugs.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Duplicate UUIDs can also occur due to error with the UUID versions generated using processes such as random number generation or hashing.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] It is important, for example, to have a high-entropy source of randomness when generating version-4 UUIDs.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] But collisions can also occur without error with such UUIDs, due to chance -- "bad luck".
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The probability of this is normally so small that it can be ignored, and can be computed precisely based on analysis of the birthday problem.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] This number would be equivalent to generating 1 billion UUIDs per second for about 86 years.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] A file containing this many UUIDs, at 16 bytes per UUID, would be about 43.4 exabytes (37.7 EiB) -- a file, listing only identifiers, a few orders of magnitude larger than the largest databases currently in existence, which are on the order of 100 PB (e.g.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] If generated according to the standards, duplicate UUIDs are more likely to be the result of bit-flips (a so called Single-event upset) caused by cosmic rays passing through memory or disk storage, than the result of mischance at UUID-generation time.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, the probability to find a duplicate within 103 trillion properly-generated version-4 UUIDs is one in a billion.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Several filesystem types (for example, ext4 and Btrfs) use a UUID to uniquely identify each filesystem to the operating system.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Filesystem userspace tools, most of which are derived from the original implementation by Theodore Ts'o, therefore make use of UUIDs.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The GUID Partition Table (GPT) uses UUIDs (called there "GUID"s) to identify partitions and partition types.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Unique partition IDs are assigned locally by the operating system.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Partition type IDs are well-known numbers, usually assigned by operating-system or hardware vendors.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] UUIDs are commonly used as a unique key in database tables.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The NEWID function in Microsoft SQL Server version 4 Transact-SQL returns standard random version-4 UUIDs, while the NEWSEQUENTIALID function returns 128-bit identifiers similar to UUIDs which are committed to ascend in sequence until the next system reboot.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The Oracle Database SYS_GUID function does not return a standard GUID, despite the name.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] Instead, it returns a 16-byte 128-bit RAW value based on a host identifier and a process or thread identifier, somewhat similar to a GUID.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] PostgreSQL contains a UUID datatype and can generate most versions of UUIDs through the use of functions from modules.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] MySQL provides a UUID function which generates standard version-1 UUIDs.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] The random nature of standard UUIDs of versions 3, 4, and 5, and the ordering of the fields within standard versions 1 and 2 may create problems with database locality or performance when UUIDs are used as primary keys.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] For example, in 2002 Jimmy Nilsson reported a significant improvement in performance with Microsoft SQL Server when the version-4 UUIDs being used as keys were modified to include a non-random suffix based on system time.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] By reordering and encoding version-1 and -2 UUIDs so that the timestamp comes first, insertion performance loss can be averted.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] This is the rationale for variant 1 (DCE) versions 6 and 7, standardized in RFC 9562.
[src:uuid-generation/universally-unique-identifier] UEFI and ACPI are examples that use GUID.
[src:uuid-generation/uuidjs-uuid] Starting with `uuid@12` CommonJS is no longer supported.
[src:uuid-generation/uuidjs-uuid] See implications and motivation for details.
[src:uuid-generation/uuidjs-uuid] For timestamp UUIDs, namespace UUIDs, and other options read on ...
[src:uuid-generation/uuidjs-uuid] Ordering of values in the byte arrays used by `parse()` and `stringify()` follows the left ↠ right order of hex-pairs in UUID strings.
[src:uuid-generation/uuidjs-uuid] API is identical to `v5()`, but uses "v3" instead.
[src:uuid-generation/uuidjs-uuid] The RFC `DNS` and `URL` namespaces are available as `v5.DNS` and `v5.URL`.
[src:uuid-generation/uuidjs-uuid] This method takes the same arguments as uuid.v1().
[src:uuid-generation/uuidjs-uuid] Version 8 (experimental) UUIDs are "for experimental or vendor-specific use cases".
[src:uuid-generation/uuidjs-uuid] The RFC does not define a creation algorithm for them, which is why this package does not offer a `v8()` method.
[src:uuid-generation/uuidjs-uuid] The `validate()` and `version()` methods do work with such UUIDs, however.
[src:uuid-generation/uuidjs-uuid] Using `validate` and `version` together it is possible to do per-version validation, e.g. validate for only v4 UUIds.
[src:uuid-generation/uuidjs-uuid] This method returns `0` for the `NIL` UUID, and `15` for the `MAX` UUID.
[src:uuid-generation/uuidjs-uuid] UUIDs can be generated from the command line using `uuid`.
[src:uuid-generation/uuidjs-uuid] The default is to generate version 4 UUIDS, however the other versions are supported.
[src:uuid-generation/uuidjs-uuid] Prior to `uuid@11`, it was possible for `options` state to interfere with the internal state used to ensure uniqueness of timestamp-based UUIDs (the `v1()`, `v6()`, and `v7()` methods).
[src:uuid-generation/uuidjs-uuid] This error occurs in environments where the standard `crypto.getRandomValues()` API is not supported.
